Those folders appear because your publish step is still mixing **package-style** and **file-system publish** settings.

You changed to:

```yaml
/p:WebPublishMethod=FileSystem
```

but you still pass:

```yaml
/p:PackageLocation="..."
```

`PackageLocation` belongs to the **package/web deploy** flow, not the plain file-system publish flow. In Visual Studio web publishing, package settings and file-system publish settings are different concepts. ([Microsoft Learn][1])

That is why you end up with a structure like:

```text
Archive\Content\C_C\agent\_work\6\s\CardManagement\SGBL.CardManagement\obj\Any CPU\Release\Package\PackageTmp
```

This is classic **web package archive structure**, where the real site content is placed under `PackageTmp`, and the archive preserves the source path. It is not the flat IIS-ready folder you want.

## What to change

In your build template, replace this publish step:

```yaml
- task: VSBuild@1
  displayName: 'Publish (Package)'
  condition: and(succeeded(), ne('${{ parameters.buildProject }}', ''))
  inputs:
    solution: '${{ parameters.buildProject }}'
    vsVersion: '${{ parameters.vsVersion }}'
    platform: '${{ parameters.buildPlatform }}'
    configuration: '${{ parameters.buildConfiguration }}'
    clean: false
    msbuildArgs: >
      /p:VisualStudioVersion=${{ parameters.vsVersion }}
      /p:DeployOnBuild=true
      /p:WebPublishMethod=FileSystem
      /p:DeleteExistingFiles=true
      /p:PackageAsSingleFile=false
      /p:SkipInvalidConfigurations=true
      /p:PackageLocation="${{ parameters.packageLocation }}"
      /p:AutoParameterizationWebConfigConnectionStrings=false
```

with this:

```yaml
- task: VSBuild@1
  displayName: 'Publish to folder'
  condition: and(succeeded(), ne('${{ parameters.buildProject }}', ''))
  inputs:
    solution: '${{ parameters.buildProject }}'
    vsVersion: '${{ parameters.vsVersion }}'
    platform: '${{ parameters.buildPlatform }}'
    configuration: '${{ parameters.buildConfiguration }}'
    clean: false
    msbuildArgs: >
      /p:VisualStudioVersion=${{ parameters.vsVersion }}
      /p:DeployOnBuild=true
      /p:WebPublishMethod=FileSystem
      /p:DeleteExistingFiles=true
      /p:publishUrl="${{ parameters.packageLocation }}"
      /p:SkipInvalidConfigurations=true
      /p:AutoParameterizationWebConfigConnectionStrings=false
```

## Also remove these for file-system publish

Do **not** use these together with `WebPublishMethod=FileSystem`:

```yaml
/p:PackageAsSingleFile=false
/p:PackageLocation="..."
```

They are package-oriented settings, not file-copy publish settings. ([Microsoft Learn][1])

## What you should get after the fix

Inside `${{ parameters.packageLocation }}` you should see the actual website files directly, for example:

```text
Web.config
bin\
Content\
Views\
Global.asax
```

Then `ArchiveFiles@2` will create a normal zip, and when your deploy stage extracts it, your `**/Web.config` rule will work.

## Why `PackageTmp` showed up

`PackageTmp` is the staging folder used by the old ASP.NET web publishing/package pipeline. It is normal in package scenarios, but it is not what you want for your current IIS copy deployment flow. ([Microsoft Learn][1])

## Final corrected publish section

Use this exact block:

```yaml
- task: VSBuild@1
  displayName: 'Publish to folder'
  condition: and(succeeded(), ne('${{ parameters.buildProject }}', ''))
  inputs:
    solution: '${{ parameters.buildProject }}'
    vsVersion: '${{ parameters.vsVersion }}'
    platform: '${{ parameters.buildPlatform }}'
    configuration: '${{ parameters.buildConfiguration }}'
    clean: false
    msbuildArgs: >
      /p:VisualStudioVersion=${{ parameters.vsVersion }}
      /p:DeployOnBuild=true
      /p:WebPublishMethod=FileSystem
      /p:DeleteExistingFiles=true
      /p:publishUrl="${{ parameters.packageLocation }}"
      /p:SkipInvalidConfigurations=true
      /p:AutoParameterizationWebConfigConnectionStrings=false
```

After that, your deploy template should start seeing `Web.config` in the extracted folder.

